Transgender Rights Movement¶

The transgender rights movement has been growing in the public eye since the early 2010s, and has been a subject of massive popular and political controversy throughout the United States and abroad. Transgender individuals are people who identify as a gender other than the one they were assigned at birth. Stemming from the LGBT movement, which has gained massive momentum and many legislative victories since 2000, the transgender rights movement has similarly pushed for new legislation on multiple fronts, to allow them. Many people see this push as a civil rights movement, in which the trans community is pushing for equal rights to all other groups. Others question the legitimacy of the claimed rights, and indeed some even question the legitimacy of being transgender at all.

Many Battlegrounds¶

Gender-Specific Activities and Areas¶

Many prominent policy/public opinion battle-grounds related to the topic of transgender revolve around whether transgender individuals should be granted admission into gender-specific areas corresponding to their gender identity, or whether they should/can be restricted to the gender they were assigned to at birth:

  • Using male/female public restrooms
  • Admission into all-male/all-female schools and colleges
  • Participation in male/female sports divisions

Health and Gender-Affirming Care¶

Other issues revolve around the use of certain medical treatments, such as the administration of hormone blockers, on transgender people under the age of 18. Medical procedures for transgender people are often lumped together under the term 'gender-affirming care', although this term includes a wide variety of medical procedures with varying degrees of impact on the body. For exampe, Alabama House Bill 1, introduced in 2021, attempted to prevent minors from receiving medication intended to 'alter the appearance of the minor child's gender or delay puberty', although the bill died on the house floor later that year (Alabama HB1).

Discrimination and Violence¶

An unfortunately large issue affecting the trans community is called 'transmysogyny', and is, simply put, discrimination and violence directed towards transgender individuals. According to a survey conducted by the National Coalition of Anti-Violence Programs (NCAVP), black transgender individuals are particularly at risk for violence. Of 17 homicides of trans and gender-nonconforming people counted by the NCAVP in 2017, 16 had been people of color; 15 had been transgender women; and 13 had been black transgender women(Waters).

A Divided Public¶

A Pew Research Center poll recently found that american public opinion sharply divided on trans individuals, and the degree to which their gender identities should be accepted, affirmed, and/or protected by society. For example, while a majority of americans (64%) supporedt legislation that would "protect trans people from discrimination in jobs, housing, and public spaces", a sizeable minority (10%) opposed/strongly opposed such legislation. In the same poll, 38% of americans surveyed said that the US 'has gone too far in accepting' trans people, while 36% said that the US 'hasn't gone far enough'. In addition, people's opinions on these issues were drastically influenced by the political party they identified with. Here's a concrete list of issues covered by the survey.

This Project's Purpose¶

While public opinion is sharply divided on the subject of Trans rights, it's often murky or unclear exactly where the division is between the two sides. This analysis of News Articles with the key-word transgender attempts to shed light on the events of the trans rights movement in recent months, and the differing opinions thereof.

#Preparing the WorldNews dataFrames for the creation of Word-Clouds. Creating a running total count of word frequency and returning
#A numeric Series of the 100 most frequent words, indexed by word, and containing frequency. We can use this to build the word-cloud.
dfs=[worldnews_title_c,worldnews_text_c]
wc_sums=[]
titles=['WorldNewsAPI (Title)','WorldNewsAPI (Text)']

for df in dfs:
    df.iloc[:,4:]=df.iloc[:,4:].apply(pd.to_numeric)
    wc_sums += [df.iloc[:,4:].sum()[:100]]
    
#Same for GroundNews
dfs=[groundnews_title_c,groundnews_text_c]
titles+=['GroundNews (Title)','GroundNews (Text)']

for df in dfs:
    df.iloc[:,5:]=df.iloc[:,5:].apply(pd.to_numeric)
    wc_sums += [df.iloc[:,5:].sum()[:100]]

#Finally, same for NewsAPI
#Same for GroundNews
dfs=[news_title_c,news_text_c]
titles+=['NewsAPI (Title)','NewsAPI (Text)']

for df in dfs:
    df.iloc[:,5:]=df.iloc[:,5:].apply(pd.to_numeric)
    wc_sums += [df.iloc[:,5:].sum()[:100]]

#Making Word Clouds from the Various News Sources.
wordclouds = [WordCloud().generate_from_frequencies(sums) for sums in wc_sums]
fig,ax=plt.subplots(3,2,constrained_layout = True)
for i in range(3):
    for j in range(2):
        ax[i,j].imshow(wordclouds[2*i+j])
        ax[i,j].set_title(titles[2*i+j])

First Thoughts¶

In all three data sources, we appeared to get much stronger results by looking at the title than by looking at the text. This is likely because of the presence of specific 'semi-stop' words which don't convey the prime meaning of the story, but nevertheless occur often in a news article. These are words like news and said, which are very prominent in the web-scraped Ground News source text, along with time-words such as day, week, month, year, etc.

Some other thoughts:¶

  • The GroundNews Text appears to be the weakest in terms of strong meaning conveyed by the WordCloud.
    • This makes sense as it was scraped from websites with disparate HTML sources.
  • NewsAPI's Text contains an odd most popular word, char, which I can't really explain the presence of.
    • This text came from an API and wasn't scraped, so the text content should contain only the actual text. I wonder if this is due to an encoding error on python's part.
  • Since the topic is Transgender, it seems a good test of text quality that the most popular word in the wordcloud is, in fact, transgender. This is true for all three Title data-sets, so I'll work with them primarily.
    • This trend may not hold for TFIDF analysis. I'll keep using a variety of text datasets, as long as I have them available. But we're testing the titles first and foremost.
